metadata.name: Fantasmagoria #74
metadata.description:
‚Ñπ see Phantasmagoria - noun - A dreamlike state where real and imagined elements are blurred together.

üí°The work on this series started with an exploration on perceived shapes in a complex generator using noise and randomisation.

üëªThe deeper I was going into my exploration, the more I encountered scary or spooky iterations.

üßô‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èInspired by the art initiated by Paul Philidor or √âtienne-Gaspard Robertson, I decided to explore the creation of alternate, disturbing, undefined forms in the dark.

üëãüèª Personally, Fantasmagoria is a catharcis, and might be the last piece of my "dark" phase. Releasing this project means a lot, not only from the work I've put in it, but from the chapter of my life it closes.

metadata.name: Acequia #14
metadata.description:
Acequia (‚Äúah-seh-kee-uh‚Äù) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sƒÅqiya, meaning ‚Äúwater carrier‚Äù. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

‚Ä®Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions. ‚Ä®‚Ä®
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: horizon(te)s #334
metadata.description:
For this collaboration we focused on horizons as an organizing principle.  What are the edges and borders of our vision and what do we see there?

Rather than create *one* collective piece where we mix our styles, we instead opted to create essentially a series of works ‚Äì focusing on our own personal responses to the prompt as well as how we imagine the other responding to the prompt.  Each of us took on three challenges as central modes: 

Me as me 
Me as you 
Me as you as me

Each mode has a variety of variations.  This framework allowed for speculation, ambiguity, and time to reflect on our own voice and the voice of our collaborator.   The idea was not to mimic styles but rather use this framework to try to have a conversation and explore what we see in each other‚Äôs work.   

Zach: 

For me as me, I created a series of block / glitch based images on a simple horizon.  I love creating color field compositions and often find myself staring at them ‚Äì especially the subtle and luminous ones.  They seemed well suited for exploring horizons.

For me as you, I focused on Iskra‚Äôs use of layers and simple geometry for creating compositions that reframe space.   I am a huge fan of her work ‚Äì especially how she elevates and uses simple geometry and creates ambiguous forms that reference architectural structures so I enjoyed exploring what I could do with a constraint of just using rectangles.   I see blocks, windows and portals.  

For me as you as me, I explored light.   Although Iskra‚Äôs compositions often use densely overlapped lines and forms there is often a really luminous and airy quality to her works that I deeply resonate with.  She creates curtains and shapes we can see through and I tried to imagine a form of light curtain that Iskra would create to generate my work.  In this mode, a set of color bands are organized along a horizon and overlap to create new spaces and forms. 

Iskra:

Working with Zach has been a challenge and a trigger to go beyond my own expectations, limits and the technology itself. Once we made the decision of splitting the work into these three approaches we basically focused on knowing better each one and our work.

Starting with the most difficult mode for me ‚ÄúMe as you ‚Äù (How could I recreate the magic lights of Zach?)  After some integration work, I got into something minimal and played with colors, contrast and shadows to recreate this feelight of shine, in my case using just lines. 

For ‚ÄúMe as you as me‚Äù I came up immediately with the idea of candies. Not sure why, but somehow I found colors and positive vibes very much associated with Zach‚Äôs work and I tried to recreate this idea by playing with sparks, flashes and vivid tones.

Last, ‚ÄúMe as Me‚Äù has been like my safe space. I changed easily through more than 5 different systems before getting the right one. The whole project is about Horizons and the idea of divisions, so I decided to focus on the concept of sea. Either a port or a mystic sailing boat, both have some disturbing elements in the scene. Sometimes a mesh ‚Äìis it possible to reflect this smell of iron? And sometimes an undefined stone cave ‚Äì is it there to protect us, or to attack us?

-----------

Artist notes  ‚Äì

Notes by Iskra: 

I highly recommend using Chrome for my pieces, especially for high res and downloads. Other browsers as Firefox or Safari have sometimes difficulties to display the work properly due to the structure of thin lines, compositions and overlaps of many of the outputs. 

Notes by Zach: 

My sketches require webgl and a relatively newer / modern browser.   Best / optimized for desktop.

For high resolution and saving on all modes ‚Äì
Press ‚Äúh‚Äù to set a high resolution mode.  Alternatively, press ‚Äúm‚Äù to increase the resolution until you want (or until your device allows it) and ‚Äúl‚Äù to reduce it. Use ‚Äús‚Äù to save the current resolution.

metadata.name: Obscure Archive #34
metadata.description:
Tabula rasa - we are all born without mental condition built-in, therefore knowledge and emotions come from experience.

As we grow up, emotions and feelings come to us naturally. Joy, sadness, anger, tranquility, confusion - to name a few, all these emotions makes us who we are today consciously or subconsciously. Yet, negative emotions are easier to remember and sticks longer compared to the positive ones.

Though, some people are lucky enough to be able to express their emotions freely to their surrounding, letting others know what they're feeling & what they've been through. While some other finds it harder to let go of those negative emotions. Wanting them to be gone but, alas, they can't find the right conditions to do so. Or even worse, these emotions get mixed up and tangled with their thoughts and memories making it harder to read or express.

__________

Obscure Archive is trying to capture what I (or maybe, you too) have been feeling constantly. These negative emotions is expressed and written as the text within the artwork, with the supergraphic representing thoughts & memories that we have. Some of the artwork has no overlay, just like those who can express their emotions freely. While some other have a completely different overlay, with messy text and supergraphic representing the concealment & entangled thoughts that make the emotions harder to read.

__________

made with ‚ù§Ô∏è and p5js

metadata.name: Terraria #15
metadata.description:
The ecosystems of our planet are becoming ever more endangered. Over 1 million animal and plant species are now threatened with extinction ‚Äî more than ever before in human history. We need to remind ourselves of the priceless value these ecosystems hold to all of us before it‚Äôs too late.

Span created the Terraria project to turn ecosystems into collectables. 3D terrariums emerge from custom letterforms, each containing one of nine different biomes ‚Äî grasslands, wetlands, mountain, tundra, rainforest, stream, desert, ocean, and forest. NFTS of each biome can be minted based on your transaction, each varied with multiple weather and time-of-day variations as well as rarities.

metadata.name: Staccato #480
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Containing just three basic repeating shapes, 'Staccato' is inspired by minimalist geometric art.
Each 'Staccato' output forms a bold, colorful and (hopefully) pleasing design.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: RE/Posizioni #170
metadata.description:
Exactly one year ago I was minting my first fxhash project. 
‚ÄúPosizioni‚Äù was a quick sketch of only 25 editions that I put together to test this new platform and to my great surprise, it was the start of an amazing journey in this space that still continues to amaze me every day. 

‚ÄúRE/Posizioni‚Äù is an ideal continuation of my personal path that started one year ago: I decided to create an animated, glitchy, or even broken piece, something completely different from what I usually do as an artist and as a coder (and probably something I‚Äôm not very good at, forgive me for this :D ).
Even if this NFT crazy world is often uncertain, insecure, or unstable, we need to find a balance no matter how difficult, just as the lines in this artwork try to do.

Going out of my comfort zone, experimenting, or just having fun is what keeps this creative practice enjoyable for me, and it‚Äôs all that matters.

----

- Mouse click to pause the animation
- "s" key to download a png
- "f" key to full screen

Tested on Desktop/Chrome.
See LICENSE.md for more licensing details.

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss TWO #228
metadata.description:
TWO combines a couple of distribution algorithms, one that creates a mesh with different variations and the other that plays with packing probabilities.

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (30-60 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

TWO is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

de/
/boss
em/

100% code, made with p5js
See License.md

metadata.name: L-Template #966
metadata.description:
THIS IS NOT AN ARTWORK.

Instead: a framework to store artwork data components onchain by including them as features in the token's smart contract. The stored data are parameters of a Lindenmayer System, which is a formal grammar that was initially conceived of as a theory of plant growth. L-Systems can model complex forms of plants using relatively few simple rules. Custom rules are generated during the minting of each token, based on the transaction hash string. 

The idea is that each iteration of the artwork can be reproduced accurately using an L-System interpreter by accessing the tezos blockchain through the FxHash API (GraphQL) and interpreting token metadata.

Reusable template source: https://github.com/x-terrain/x-terrain.github.io/tree/main/L-Template

Part of an ongoing project with RefractionDAO
